  <h1>What is Lower Deduction Certificate?</h1>
  <div class="byline"><span class="av">SR</span><b>NumberIQ Glossary</b><span class="sep"></span><span>Last reviewed June 2026</span></div>
</header>
<div class="divide"></div>

<article class="prose read">
  <p class="answer-first lead"><b>A lower deduction certificate is an order under Section 197 authorising TDS at a lower or nil rate where normal TDS would exceed the payee's likely tax liability.</b></p>
  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <p>The payee applies in Form 13; the Assessing Officer issues a certificate specifying the rate, amount and deductors, which the deductor then applies.</p>
  <div class="callout law"><b>Reference.</b> Section 197; Rule 28AA.</div>
  <div class="faq"><h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
    <details><summary>What is a lower deduction certificate?</summary><p>An AO order under Section 197 allowing TDS at a reduced or nil rate, obtained via Form 13.</p></details>
    <details><summary>Who should apply?</summary><p>Payees whose normal TDS would exceed their actual tax, such as loss-makers or refund cases.</p></details>
  </div>
  <div class="key-takeaways"><h2>Key takeaways</h2><ul><li>Section 197 certificate fixes a lower/nil TDS rate.</li><li>Applied for in Form 13.</li><li>Useful for loss-makers and refund cases.</li></ul></div>
